<DOC><DOCNO> AP881206-0238 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 1455EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   12-06 0224</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0233</SECOND><HEAD>London Shares Close Higher In Light Trading</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with closing prices</NOTE><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Share prices closed higher on London's StockExchange Tuesday, helped by a string of favorable corporate earningsreports and by a continued good performance on Wall Street.   But trading activity was light as many players remained on thesidelines amid uncertainty over whether the market has to fallfurther following its recent sharp declines.   ``People aren't in a hurry to buy at the moment. They just wantto see which way the market is going,'' said one equity saleswoman.   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 5.8points, or 0.3 percent at 1,767.4, at the close, roughly at themidpoint of the day's trading range.   The Financial Times 30-share index finished with a gain of 5.8points at 1,444.8.   Volume was light, as 466.4 million shares changed hands.   The volume figure was sharply lower than Monday's total of 645.4million shares, when volume was inflated by massive turnover of 261million shares in formerly government-owned British Steel PLC on itsfirst day of trading.   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 6.22points at 2,129.98 at the London close, extending its more than30-point rally on Monday.   The Financial Times 500-share index rose 2.31 points to close at995.30.</TEXT></DOC>